To change the app state to active after mounting your component with a mocked app state of background, you can use jest.runAllTimers() to fast-forward the timer to the next tick. This should trigger a change in the app state to active. You can then use jest.runOnlyPendingTimers() to advance the timer to the next tick and check the app state again to verify that it has changed to active.

Here is an example:


```
import React from 'react';
import AppState from 'app-state';

// Mocked AppState module
jest.mock('app-state', () => {
 return {
 currentState: 'background',
 addEventListener: jest.fn()
 };
});

describe('MyComponent', () => {
 it('should change the app state to active when mounted', () => {
 // Render the component
 const wrapper = mount(<MyComponent />);

 // Fast-forward the timer to the next tick
 jest.runAllTimers();

 // Check the app state
 expect(AppState.currentState).toBe('active');

 // Advance the timer to the next tick
 jest.runOnlyPendingTimers();

 // Check the app state again
 expect(AppState.currentState).toBe('active');
 });
});
```
